# /ai-audit

> A quick read on where AI fits in your practice — without threatening what makes you great.

## What This Skill Does

Most AI readiness tools are techno-utopian slop that frame every
creative's job as "10x your output" and alienate them in the first
sentence. This skill does the opposite.

It takes creative professionals seriously: it assumes you got into
this work because you care about the craft, that you're rightly
protective of your creative step, and that the real value of AI is
removing friction *around* the work, not automating the work itself.

The skill:

1. **Scores 5 sharpened categories** — Ops & Admin, Creative
   Workflow, Client/Stakeholder Comms, Knowledge & IP, Commercials
   & Intelligence — on a CMMI-inspired 1-5 ladder
2. **Scores Protected Zone strength per category** — the
   differentiator. Users who score high on automation but low on
   protected zones are in more danger than the reverse.
3. **Compares to practitioner-view benchmarks** segmented by
   discipline and team size so the output answers "is that good?"
   not just "here's your score"
4. **Selects 3-5 quick wins from a curated library** (never
   invented) — each mapped to a real CreativeStack skill, filtered
   by lowest category, discipline, user type, and AI maturity tier
5. **Adapts to discipline** with one targeted question per discipline
   that signals the skill understands the user's actual work
6. **Branches for AI-advanced users** so embedded-tool users don't
   get patronised with beginner content
7. **Writes to the brain** (opt-in) as a dated artefact so repeat
   runs show measurable delta — the single highest-leverage
   compounding feature
8. **Produces mode-appropriate output variants** — markdown +
   Slack summary in Snapshot, exec one-pager in Leadership Pack,
   slide outline + change management plan in Team Workshop, all of
   the above in Deep Audit

The subtle consulting CTA lives in a two-line footer, not a sales
section. Usefulness is the lead-gen strategy; "get in touch" is a
consequence, not a pitch.

## Modes

**Snapshot** (default) — 10-minute self-assessment. Produces
maturity scores, top 3 opportunities, 3-5 quick wins, skill map,
protected zone reading, Slack summary. The "which CreativeStack
skills matter most for me" trigger.

**Leadership Pack** — Snapshot intake + 2 extra stakeholder
questions. Output is restructured for a CEO/board audience:
headline maturity with benchmark comparison, executive one-pager,
ROI framing in £/hours, risk/opportunity matrix, protected zone
statement, and a condensed change-management plan. The "present
our AI strategy" trigger.

**Team Workshop** — 15-20 minute intake asked round-robin style
across multiple team member perspectives. Surfaces disagreements
(where the CD thinks ops is fine but the PM thinks it's broken)
as a distinct output section. Produces workshop-ready slide outline
and the full bringing-your-team-along plan from
`references/change-management.md`. The "creative lead building
internal case" trigger.

**Deep Audit** — Snapshot intake + workflow walkthrough ("walk me
from brief arriving to work delivered") + explicit tool stack
review against `tools.md`. Includes prior-audit delta if one
exists. Deliberately lighter than a real consulting engagement —
ends with a clean handoff note for users who want the human
version. The "we ran Snapshot 6 months ago, how have we moved?"
trigger.

