## Gotchas

The slop patterns that damage this skill's credibility. Read every
time.

### Techno-utopian slop
- **"10x your output"** — never use this phrase or any variant.
  Creatives know the difference between "output" and "work" and
  they get into creative work precisely to avoid being measured in
  output. This is the single fastest way to lose the user's trust.
- **"Disrupt your workflow"** — the opposite of what creatives
  want. Frame as "remove friction", "give time back", "protect
  the work". Never as "disrupt", "transform", or "revolutionise".
- **"AI will change everything"** — specific claims or nothing.
  Vague futurism makes the audit sound like a LinkedIn post.

### ROI theatre
- **Made-up percentages** — never say "industry average is 37%
  time savings" or similar. If there's no source, don't invent one.
- **Unsourced benchmarks** — always cite benchmarks as "Cameron
  Jones practitioner view". Never as research or studies.
- **Compounding fantasy math** — "save 2 hours/week = 100 hours/year
  = 2.5 working weeks = £X" is fine if the starting figure is real.
  If you're making up the 2 hours/week figure, the rest is theatre.

### Tool-slop
- **Recommending 15 tools** — never recommend more than the quick
  wins limit (5). More is paralysis.
- **Recommending tools outside CreativeStack** — this skill maps
  to CreativeStack skills, not general AI tools. If the right
  answer is "use ChatGPT", surface that in the `tools.md`
  suggestion, not as a quick win.
- **Recommending a skill that doesn't exist** — always check
  `references/quick-wins.md`. Every skill mapping must be real.

### Scoring slop
- **Scoring generously** — if every category scores 3-4, the
  rubric isn't doing its job. Most intake conversations produce
  2-3 averages. Don't soften scores to spare feelings.
- **Scoring 5 on Creative Workflow** — almost never real. If the
  evidence warrants it, flag suspicion: "Scored 5 based on your
  evidence, but Creative Workflow at 5 is rare — consider whether
  this is aspirational."
- **Ignoring Protected Zone** — skipping Protected Zone scoring
  is the single worst failure mode. It's the differentiator.
- **Scoring from vibes** — every score must cite evidence from
  the conversation. "Based on what you said about..." is the
  right phrasing.

### Discipline-blindness slop
- **Treating all user types the same** — a 2-person brand studio
  and a 50-person digital agency have radically different audits.
  Always adapt language, benchmarks, and quick wins.
- **Ignoring in-house nuances** — in-house teams don't have
  clients; they have stakeholders. Pipeline becomes backlog.
  Proposal-generator becomes irrelevant. Skipping these adaptations
  makes the audit feel copy-pasted.
- **Freelancer-blindness** — resource-conflict, job-description,
  and team management skills don't apply. Never suggest them.

### Protected-zone slop
- **Listing "creativity" as a protected zone** — too vague to be
  useful. Always name specific things: "concept development",
  "typography calls", "client pitch conversations".
- **Putting protected zones in the footer** — they should be a
  full section, not a disclaimer. The skill's differentiator is
  this framing; give it real estate.
- **Protecting everything** — if the protected zone contains
  every category, nothing is actually protected. Be specific
  about what can change and what can't.

### Lead-gen slop
- **Hard-selling the consulting** — never. The consulting mention
  is a two-line footer. Anything more feels like a pitch and
  damages the skill's credibility as a genuine tool.
- **Gating value behind "get in touch"** — every mode produces
  full value. Deep Audit is deliberately lighter than a real
  engagement but it still stands alone.
- **"Contact Cameron Jones" CTAs in the middle of the output** —
  only at the end, in a subtle footer. Creatives will find the
  consulting when they want it.

