## Edge Cases

- **No brain at all** → use neutral language ("your work", "your
  clients"), skip type-specific adaptations, end with a strong
  nudge to `/creativestack:setup` for next time.
- **Brain exists but very thin** (profile only) → run the audit
  but note reduced depth in the output header.
- **User is AI-advanced** → branch per Step 5. Never patronise.
- **User is AI-beginner and nervous** → lean heavily on the
  Protected Zone content, keep ROI language grounded (hours saved,
  not revenue growth), skip advanced quick wins.
- **User is hostile to AI** → the skill still works. Shift the
  framing entirely to "protect what makes you great" — lead with
  the Protected Zone section, treat quick wins as "experiments to
  run", and de-emphasise maturity scoring. The goal is to leave
  them with something useful, not to convert them.
- **Answers are very short** → work with what you have, add a
  Low confidence label, recommend a longer intake next time.
- **Prior audit exists with different rubric version** → show
  absolute scores only, note that direct delta isn't possible due
  to rubric change, point at the rubric version field in both
  audits.
- **Team Workshop mode with a solo operator** → gracefully degrade
  to Snapshot mode with a note ("Team Workshop needs a team of 2+").
- **Leadership Pack mode but the user is the leader** → still
  works. Frame the executive one-pager as "what you'd tell the
  board", not "what you'd tell your CEO".
- **User runs this as part of a CreativeStack demo** → respect
  the privacy note, skip brain writeback offers, don't compound.
- **Multiple audits in one day** → honour subsequent runs but
  flag ("Second audit today — unusual, are you iterating?").

